{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ac5226a2-d2ac-4911-a66e-126028be7048","content":"Here's the mapping and the new command:\n\n| VSTest flag | Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalent | NuGet package needed |\n|---|---|---|\n| `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` | `--treenode-filter \"/**/TestCategory=Integration\"` | *(built-in)* |\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--collect-coverage` + config | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\n**New command** (run per test project on .NET 8):\n\n```bash\ndotnet run --project <Test.csproj> -- \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/**/TestCategory=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --collect-coverage \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**For Cobertura output**, add a `.runsettings` or a coverage config file:\n\n```xml\n<!-- coverage.config -->\n<Configuration>\n  <CodeCoverage>\n    <Format>cobertura</Format>\n  </CodeCoverage>\n</Configuration>\n```\n\nThen pass `--collect-coverage-settings coverage.config`.\n\n> **Note:** On .NET 8, `dotnet test` doesn't natively forward args to Microsoft.Testing.Platform â€” use `dotnet run --project` (or the built executable directly). Native `dotnet test` integration arrives in .NET 9.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"52a173a9-36b2-4fbe-8e65-39701929d3f4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences with Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n- `--filter` becomes `--filter`(same) or `--treenode-filter`\n- `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` becomes `--collect-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage, or you use a different approach\n- `--blame-crash` becomes `--crashdump`\n\n\n- `--blame-hang` and `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` becomes `--hangdump` and `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can run the test executable directly or use `dotnet run`, but `dotnet test` with `--` still works to pass platform-specific options. The filter syntax remains the same, though the platform supports additional filtering options like `--treenode-filter`.\n\nThe key switches change to `--report-trx` for TRX logging, `--collect-coverage` for code coverage, `--crashdump` for crash dumps, and `--hangdump` with `--hangdump-timeout` for hang detectionâ€”each requiring their respective extension packages. When using `dotnet test`, these options go after the `--` separator. Finishing the command syntax...\n\nI'm realizing the filter syntax differs between VSTest and Microsoft.Testing.Platformâ€”the newer platform uses `--treenode-filter` with a different format, though there's a compatibility layer. For the clearest migration, I'd keep `--filter` as a `dotnet test` argument before the `--` separator, then pass the platform-specific options like coverage collection and dump settings after it. I need to clarify the .NET 8 vs .NET 9 distinction hereâ€”on .NET 8, `dotnet test` doesn't have native Microsoft.Testing.Platform support, so running the test executable directly with `dotnet run` is the more reliable approach, passing the platform-specific arguments like treenode filters, coverage collection, and dump options directly to the test runner. I should simplify this and focus on what the user actually needsâ€”the updated command with the required packages and a clear mapping of each flag to its purpose.","outputTokens":2058,"requestId":"0421:2EB5E6:1F996E6:236D723:69E81AC2"},"id":"ff47dd21-2d54-4aa2-9638-3303bcdc219a","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:48:38.327Z","parentId":"baebcde6-658f-48fd-95c3-ba6d